			<h2> Here's a time line of Tolkien's life &#8675 </h2>
		</div>
	</section>
	<!-- Timeline -->
	<section class="timeline">
		<ul>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>3 January 1892</time>
					Birth of John Ronald Reuel Tolkien in Bloemfontein, Orange Free State (now part of South Africa).
				</div>
			</li>
			 <li>
				<div>
					<time>Autumn Term 1907</time>	Tolkien probably invents his private language ‘Naffarin’ based on Spanish and Latin.
				</div>
			</li>
			 <li>
				<div>
					<time>17 December 1910</time> 	Tolkien obtains a scholarship at Oxford’s Exeter College.
				</div>
			</li>
			 <li>
				<div>
					<time>October 1911</time> 	Tolkien begins studying at Oxford.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>24 September 1914</time>	Tolkien writes his first identifiable “Middle-earth” fragment ‘The Voyage of Éarendel the Evening Star’.
				</div>
			</li>
			 <li>
				<div>
					<time>April 1915</time>
					The poems ‘You & Me and the Cottage of Lost Play’ and ‘Kôr’ are written. Tolkien gains a First Class Honours degree. 
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>27 October 1916</time>	Tolkien reports sick.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>9 November 1916</time>	Suffering from trench fever, Tolkien returns to England.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Jan-Feb 1917</time>	Tolkien works on The Book of Lost Tales during convalescence in Great Haywood.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Spring 1917</time>	‘The Fall of Gondolin’ is probably written before June. He is posted to Yorkshire, but he suffers recurring bouts of illness.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>16 November 1917</time>	The Tolkiens’ eldest son, John, is born in Cheltenham.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>November 1918</time>	The Tolkiens return to Oxford. Tolkien obtains employment with the New English Dictionary [Oxford English Dictionary]. Tolkien probably begins work on the first version of ‘The Music of the Ainur’.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Autumn 1920</time>	He begins work as a Reader in English Language at Leeds University. Michael, the Tolkiens’ second son is born on 22 October.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>11 May 1922</time>	
			A Middle English Vocabulary is published. Tolkien and E.V. Gordon begin work on their edition of Sir Gawain and the Green Knight.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Summer 1923</time>	Convalescing from pneumonia on his brother’s farm, Tolkien turns to his mythology again, and probably works on an early form of Qenya.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>16 July 1924</time>	Tolkien is appointed as Professor of English Language at Leeds University.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Autumn 1925</time>	Tolkien takes up an appointment as Rawlinson and Bosworth Professor of Anglo-Saxon at Oxford. He purchases a house in Oxford.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Summer 1930</time>	About this time, Tolkien may have written the first sentence of The Hobbit: “In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit“.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Late? 1932</time>	Tolkien probably lends the typescript of The Hobbit to C.S. Lewis, which at this time ends with the death of Smaug.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>Autumn 1933</time>	The Inklings meetings under the auspices of C.S. Lewis become an important part of Tolkien’s social life.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>21 September 1937</time>	The Hobbit is published. Because of its success, Stanley Unwin subsequently urges Tolkien to write a sequel, which he begins. This is the germ of The Lord of the Rings.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>26-7 August 1940</time>	Tolkien invents Saruman as a reason for Gandalf’s delay in reaching Bag End in The Lord of the Rings.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>23 June 1945</time>	Tolkien becomes Oxford’s Merton Professor of English Language and Literature.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>c. Autumn 1949</time>	Tolkien begins negotiations with Milton Waldman at the publishers Collins about publishing The Lord of the Rings.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>November 1952</time>	Allen & Unwin confirm that they would like to publish The Lord of the Rings on a profit-sharing basis.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>29 July 1954</time>	Publication of The Fellowship of the Ring.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>11 November 1954</time>	Publication of The Two Towers.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>20 October 1955</time>	Publication of The Return of the King.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>22 November 1962</time>	The Adventures of Tom Bombadil is published.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>22 November 1963</time>	Death of C.S. Lewis.
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div>
					<time>2 September 1973</time>	Death of J.R.R. Tolkien from a stomach ulcer.
				</div>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>
	<h2> "Well, here at last, dear friends, on the shores of the sea comes the end of our fellowship in middle-earth. Go in peace! I will not say: do not weep for not all tears are an evil."</h2>
	<p>Gandalf,
		J.R.R. Tolkien, The Grey Havens, The Return of the King</p> 
